node.title: A woman is impaled by a corn rake, but do her fatal injuries add up to murder?
node.description: A farmer's wife is found in a shed on their Iowa farm with a corn rake lodged in her back. The rake has just four tines – so why does she have six puncture wounds?

node.title: Liz Cambage has 'zero' interest in Opals ahead of Women's World Cup
node.description: The Opals will almost certainly enter next year's Women's World Cup in Sydney without superstar Liz Cambage.

node.title: Woman rescued from roof of ute on flooded road in Western Downs
node.description: A Springvale grazier says he spotted the woman while he was using a jet ski to check on his cattle in the flood. More rain is expected in parts of southern Queensland later this week.

node.title: 6 Michigan teens charged for allegedly threatening schools
node.description: A seventh teenager was charged for allegedly possessing a weapon in a school zone.

node.title: Breakers no match for South East Melbourne Phoenix in NBL opener
node.description: An undermanned Breakers side have been put to the sword in their opening game of the NBL season.

node.title: Sydney Opera House seagull patrols a success for eateries
node.description: Dog patrols to scare away seagulls swooping on Sydney restaurant diners have been a success, with the patrol winning a repeat contract.

node.title: Sydney team unlocking more about how Omicron works
node.description: Virologist Sarah Palmer and her colleagues at Sydney's Westmead Institute virus research centre are working overtime to learn more about the Omicron variant.

node.title: Charging the parents after a US school shooting is unusual, but it has happened before
node.description: Guns used in United States school shootings have often come from the homes of young perpetrators but parents are rarely charged for the violence that occurs, experts say.

node.title: ACT records six new COVID-19 cases, confirms second Omicron infection
node.description: The ACT records six new COVID-19 cases as authorities confirm its second case of the Omicron variant. The ACT's first Omicron case has also been linked to a Sydney climbing gym.

node.title: Deputy PM says apology issued over ‘incident’ at Nationals Christmas party involving NT Senator
node.description: The office of Deputy Prime Minister Barnaby Joyce confirms an apology has been received after an incident at a Canberra pub where one witness told the ABC that Senator McMahon threw several punches towards Nationals federal director Jonathan Hawkes.

node.title: One dead and dozens burned in Indonesia eruption
node.description: One person has died and 41 have burn injuries as Mt Semuru erupts on Indonesia's Java island.

node.title: US school shooting suspect's parents deny manslaughter charges
node.description: Bail is set at $US1 million ($NZ1.4m) for the couple arrested in Detroit after failing to attend court on Friday.

node.title: What I really want for Christmas: Jackie Clark
node.description: What do people who work to improve the lives of others really want for their communities this Christmas. In the first instalment of a new RNZ series, Jackie Clark of The Aunties shares her wishlist.

node.title: Lawrence Weiner, Artist Whose Medium Was Language, Dies at 79
node.description: A pioneer of the Conceptual art movement, he used words as his métier more than any other artist of his generation.

node.title: Alabama Picks Georgia Apart, Setting Course for Another Playoff
node.description: No. 3 Alabama, the reigning national champion, fell behind early. Then it pounded the country’s best defense to run away with the Southeastern Conference championship.

node.title: To Counter China, Austin Vows to Shore Up Alliances With Others in Region
node.description: “America is a Pacific power,” the defense secretary said as he laid out a strategy to block efforts by China to dominate the region.

node.title: Florida Man Tased, Arrested for Jumping Court Railing During Wife's Sentencing for Child Abuse
node.description: "While I understand these proceedings can elicit an emotional response from loved ones, my bailiffs simply cannot allow an outburst of this kind," a sheriff said.

node.title: 911 Center Shooting Sees One Dispatcher Accidentally Kill Another While Trading Guns: Police
node.description: The two "grew up together and shared the hobby of casual gun trading," said a sheriff, adding they were "cousins and best friends."

node.title: No new community COVID cases in Queensland, six in quarantine
node.description: Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk says the cases in quarantine are not a risk to the community, but again urges people on the Gold Coast to get tested following a number of cases emerging there in recent days.

node.title: Bathurst 1000 is more than just a great race for diehard fans
node.description: The Bathurst 1000 is more than just a 161-lap race around Mount Panorama. It's about the gathering of people, year on year, and the new connections they build across a weekend of jam-packed action.

node.title: CNN fires anchor Chris Cuomo over adviser role during brother's sex scandal as New York governor
node.description: Mr Cuomo admitted in May that he had broken some of the news network's rules in advising his brother how to handle the allegations from a public relations perspective.

node.title: Man charged with manslaughter and endangerment over death of 3yo girl found in drain
node.description: Police in North Queensland say they were called to a house where two young children were reported missing. A two-year-old was found safe and well, wandering in a street, while the three-year-old girl was found in a stormwater drain at about 8:20pm.

node.title: 'I don't accept anybody's red lines': Biden and Putin to talk about Ukraine in video call
node.description: US President Joe Biden and Russian President Vladimir Putin they will hold a video call on Tuesday, with the two leaders set to discuss the tense situation in Ukraine.

node.title: Five Omicron cases linked to indoor gym, Western Sydney schools
node.description: There are now five Omicron cases connected to a cluster at an indoor climbing gym and two Western Sydney schools, bringing to 15 the total number of confirmed cases of the  COVID-19 variant across the state.

node.title: 'Today your dad is going to kill me': Family violence victim's heartbreaking text to daughter before she was killed
node.description: The Northern Territory's top cop says police have to get better at combating spiralling rates of family violence as the murder of a woman by her partner is described as "about as horrific as it gets".

node.title: European envoys may return to Afghanistan - Macron

node.title: NZ could face 'massive rise' in Covid-19 infections - Wiles

node.title: 5 Amazing New Discoveries About Mars

node.title: Autistic Nick spent years unemployed because of his disability. Now he gets paid to write about it
node.description: Nick McAllister was unemployed for 10 years and has no doubt it was because he is autistic. Now he earns a living writing about his experiences for the ABC.

node.title: Fish and chip shop owners feeling the pinch amid skyrocketing oil price
node.description: Fish and chips are a fast food favourite, but some outlets are finding it tough to make a profit. Here's why the dish is becoming more expensive — for suppliers and consumers.
